 Lake Superior -- tReflections in the Water -- tThe Lakes at Night -- tFinding Our Place -- tAfterword -- tFurther Reading -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDeclining access to fresh water is one of the twenty-first century’s most pressing environmental and human rights challenges, yet the struggle for water is not a new cause. The 8,800-kilometer border dividing Canada and the United States contains more than 20 percent of the world’s total freshwater resources, and Border Flows traces the century-long effort by Canada and the United States to manage and care for their ecologically and economically shared rivers and lakes. Ranging across the continent, from the Great Lakes to the Northwest Passage to the Salish Sea, the histories in Border Flows offer critical insights into the historical struggle to care for these vital waters. From multiple perspectives, the book reveals alternative paradigms in water history, law, and policy at scales from the local to the transnational. Students, concerned citizens, and policymakers alike will benefit from the lessons to be found along this critical international border.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWaterxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aWaterxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aWaterxLaw and legislationzCanada. 0aWaterxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aWater-supplyzCanadaxManagement. 0aWater-supplyzUnited StatesxManagement. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh  aAmerican water.  aCanada water.  aborder water.  aboundary waters treaty.  acolubmia river treaty.  afisheries management.  agreat lakes water management.  agreat lakes.  ahydro dam.  ahydroelectric dam.  ahydropolitics.  ainternational joint commis